  "notes": {
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x0": "F excels with contextual framing—the 'cruel hierarchy' of the Blockältester role is analytically rich. D is solid but reads like a report rather than a narrative. A's claim that Carlebach died in 1945 is unsupported and problematic.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x1": "E gives the best contextual grounding of the 1938 mass arrests. F is the weakest—mentioning Auschwitz and experiments when the source doesn't clearly link them to Eisner. B does well flagging uncertainty.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x2": "E is the strongest for its disciplined paraphrase. The first-person framings (A, B, C) add emotional colour but risk misrepresenting the source genre. D and F are competent middle ground.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x3": "B is excellent—adds 'Anschluss' context that is historically accurate and clarifies the Vienna reference. D is also strong with its 'chilling order' framing. F's 'Buchananwald' typo is disqualifying for a serious annotation.",
    "345ec2cb736b619c26b5e443dc6c96d9_x4": "C and E are the strongest for their analytical depth. C's reading of the SS perspective on 'negative elements' adds important interpretive nuance. A is solid but less distinctive."
  }
